Î¤118 short ode, C. i. 26, and this ode were addressed to the same person, L. Aelius Lamia (see Introduction to C. i. 26). The language of the former ode has led to the inference that Lamia was a young man of desponding disposition, and this that he was proud and vain-glorious,-a sort of criticism impertinent and unreasonable as it seems to me. What is clear is no more than that Lamia was a young man of good birth, being of the Aelia gens, who were plebeians, but of old standing. Like other families the Lamiae were per- haps glad to trace their origin to a fabulous hero, and believed their founder to be Lamus, king of the Laestrygonians, and builder of Formiae, from whence they must have mi- grated to Rome (see last ode, v. 33, n.). Horace had evidently an affection sor the young man Lamia, whose father was a friend of Cicero's, and died rich. He must have written many such that have never been published, and these two odes were probably included in the collection out of compliment to Lamia.
